            </div>
            <div type="general">
               <head>General</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Birzeit is a small town located in olive groves slightly north of Ramallah. Its inhabitants were originally mostly Arab Christians, with a Muslim minority. Due to internal migration, the majority of the population today is Muslim.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Birzeit is well known for its university, which is considered the most important in the West Bank. It was founded at the beginning of the 20th century officially as a small school for girls from the surrounding villages. During the past decades it has been a focus for Palestinian resistance and has had to endure closures and the arrest and detention of employees and students.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <head>Research history</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Blau (1960) is a detailed study on the syntax of the dialect spoken in Birzeit. This work is based on the large collection of folktales published in <hi rendition="#i">Volkserzählungen</hi><hi rendition="#i"> </hi><hi rendition="#i">aus</hi><hi rendition="#i"> </hi><hi rendition="#i">Palästina</hi> by Schmidt and Kahle (1918/30), which includes transcribed and translated texts collected in Birzeit.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Seeger’s (2009a, 2009b, 2013) investigations on the dialects spoken in the villages around Ramallah also contains information about the dialect of Birzeit: Seeger (2009a) has text samples with German translations; and Seeger (2013) is a detailed grammatical sketch and survey of the grammatical features characteristic of the region, though it is not explicitly noted where they are used exactly.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="dictionaries">
               <head>Dictionaries</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve"><rs type="bibl" ref="zotID:CS5IE6NW">Seeger 2017</rs> is very useful for the dialect of Birzeit.</p>
            </div>
